Activin A.description: Activin A (Inhibin subunit beta A) is a TGF-beta superfamily member that regulates cell proliferation, differentiation, and apoptosis. In cancer, activin A promotes tumor progression and metastasis, suppresses antitumor immunity by inducing regulatory T cells, and contributes to cancer cachexia. It is elevated in many solid tumors and correlates with poor prognosis.

BDNF.description: Brain-derived neurotrophic factor supports neuronal survival, growth, and synaptic plasticity. In immuno-oncology, BDNF promotes tumor cell survival and perineural invasion in various cancers. TrkB signaling (BDNF receptor) enhances tumor aggressiveness and resistance to anoikis, particularly in neuroblastoma, breast cancer, and pancreatic cancer.

BMP2.description: Bone morphogenetic protein 2 induces bone and cartilage formation. In cancer, BMP2 has context-dependent roles: it suppresses tumor growth in some cancers but promotes epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT) and metastasis in others. BMP2 signaling influences tumor-associated macrophage polarization and can modulate immune cell infiltration in the tumor microenvironment.

BMP4.description: Bone morphogenetic protein 4 regulates embryonic development and hematopoiesis. In immuno-oncology, BMP4 is elevated in glioblastoma and promotes cancer stem cell maintenance. It can suppress NK cell cytotoxicity and T cell responses, contributing to immune evasion. BMP4 also drives EMT and promotes tumor cell invasion and metastasis.

BMP6.description: Bone morphogenetic protein 6 regulates iron homeostasis through hepcidin induction. In cancer, BMP6 shows tumor-suppressive properties in some contexts by inhibiting tumor cell proliferation. However, in the tumor microenvironment, it can promote angiogenesis and modulate immune responses, affecting treatment outcomes in various solid tumors.

CD40L.description: CD40 ligand (CD154) is expressed on activated T cells and binds CD40 on antigen-presenting cells. In cancer immunotherapy, CD40-CD40L signaling is a key target for activating dendritic cells and enhancing antitumor immunity. Agonistic anti-CD40 antibodies are being developed to overcome immunosuppression in the tumor microenvironment and enhance T cell priming against tumor antigens.

CXCL12.description: C-X-C motif chemokine ligand 12 (SDF-1) is a homeostatic chemokine that attracts lymphocytes and stem cells. In cancer, the CXCL12-CXCR4 axis drives tumor metastasis to bone marrow and other organs, recruits immunosuppressive cells to tumors, and maintains cancer stem cells. CXCR4 antagonists are being developed to disrupt these pro-tumorigenic pathways and enhance immunotherapy response.

EGF.description: Epidermal growth factor stimulates cell proliferation by binding EGFR. In immuno-oncology, EGFR signaling promotes tumor cell survival, proliferation, and immune evasion by upregulating PD-L1 expression. Anti-EGFR therapies (cetuximab, gefitinib) can enhance antitumor immunity, and combination with checkpoint inhibitors is being explored for synergistic effects.

FGF2.description: Fibroblast growth factor 2 (basic FGF) promotes angiogenesis and tissue repair. In the tumor microenvironment, FGF2 drives tumor angiogenesis, supports cancer-associated fibroblast activation, and contributes to resistance to anti-VEGF therapy. FGF/FGFR pathway inhibitors are being developed for various cancers including bladder, lung, and hepatocellular carcinoma.

GCSF.description: Granulocyte colony-stimulating factor stimulates neutrophil production. In cancer, G-CSF mobilizes myeloid-derived suppressor cells (MDSCs) that promote tumor immune evasion. However, G-CSF is also used therapeutically to manage chemotherapy-induced neutropenia. Tumor-derived G-CSF can promote pre-metastatic niche formation and support distant metastasis.

GDF11.description: Growth differentiation factor 11 is a TGF-beta family member studied for potential anti-aging effects. In cancer, GDF11 shows context-dependent roles: it inhibits hepatocellular carcinoma growth but may promote pancreatic cancer progression. It can modulate immune cell differentiation and affect tumor microenvironment composition through TGF-beta family signaling.

GMCSF.description: Granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor promotes myeloid cell differentiation and activation. In cancer immunotherapy, GM-CSF is used as an adjuvant in cancer vaccines (GVAX, sipuleucel-T) to enhance dendritic cell function and antitumor T cell responses. However, tumor-derived GM-CSF can also recruit immunosuppressive myeloid cells, highlighting its dual role in tumor immunity.

HGF.description: Hepatocyte growth factor promotes cell proliferation and motility through c-MET receptor. In cancer, HGF/MET signaling drives tumor invasion, metastasis, and resistance to targeted therapies. It promotes immunosuppression by recruiting neutrophils and reducing T cell infiltration. MET inhibitors (crizotinib, cabozantinib) are used in lung cancer and other MET-driven tumors.

IFN1.description: Type I interferons (IFN-alpha/beta) are produced in response to viral infection. In cancer immunotherapy, type I IFNs enhance dendritic cell cross-presentation, activate NK and CD8+ T cells, and have direct antiproliferative effects on tumor cells. IFN-alpha was among the first approved cancer immunotherapies (melanoma, renal cell carcinoma) and enhances responses to checkpoint inhibitors through STING pathway activation.

IFNG.description: Interferon gamma (IFN-γ) is a key cytokine for innate and adaptive immunity. In immuno-oncology, IFN-γ is critical for antitumor immunity: it activates cytotoxic T cells and macrophages, upregulates MHC class I on tumor cells, and inhibits angiogenesis. IFN-γ signature predicts response to checkpoint inhibitors. However, chronic IFN-γ can also induce PD-L1 expression on tumors, contributing to adaptive immune resistance.

IFNL.description: Type III interferons (IFN-lambda) provide antiviral protection at epithelial barriers. In cancer, IFN-lambda has emerging roles in antitumor immunity through enhancing NK cell cytotoxicity and CD8+ T cell responses with potentially fewer systemic side effects than type I IFNs. It is being explored for cancer therapy, particularly in epithelial tumors.

IL10.description: Interleukin-10 is an anti-inflammatory cytokine that limits immune responses. In the tumor microenvironment, IL-10 has complex roles: while it suppresses antitumor immunity through regulatory T cells and M2 macrophages, pegylated IL-10 (pegilodecakin) paradoxically enhances CD8+ T cell tumor infiltration and cytotoxicity. IL-10 is being evaluated in combination with checkpoint inhibitors.

IL12.description: Interleukin-12 promotes Th1 differentiation and IFN-γ production by T and NK cells. IL-12 is a potent antitumor cytokine that enhances cytotoxic T cell and NK cell responses against tumors. Local IL-12 delivery (intratumoral injection, gene therapy, oncolytic viruses) is being developed to overcome systemic toxicity and create 'hot' tumor microenvironments responsive to immunotherapy.

IL13.description: Interleukin-13 promotes Th2 responses and alternative macrophage activation. In cancer, IL-13 can promote tumor progression by inducing immunosuppressive M2 macrophage polarization and supporting tumor cell survival. However, IL-13 receptor alpha 2 (IL13Rα2) is overexpressed on glioblastoma and other tumors, making it a target for CAR-T therapy and immunotoxin approaches.

IL15.description: Interleukin-15 supports NK cell and memory CD8+ T cell development and homeostasis. IL-15 is a key cytokine for cancer immunotherapy: it promotes expansion and persistence of cytotoxic lymphocytes without expanding regulatory T cells. IL-15 superagonists (N-803/ALT-803) are in clinical development for solid tumors and hematologic malignancies, often combined with checkpoint inhibitors.

IL17A.description: Interleukin-17A is the signature cytokine of Th17 cells. In cancer, IL-17 has paradoxical roles: it can promote tumor growth through angiogenesis and MDSC recruitment, but also enhance antitumor immunity in certain contexts. Tumor-infiltrating Th17 cells are associated with variable prognosis depending on cancer type. IL-17 pathway inhibition may enhance checkpoint inhibitor efficacy in some tumors.

IL1A.description: Interleukin-1 alpha is a pro-inflammatory cytokine and alarmin. In cancer, IL-1α released from dying tumor cells can trigger sterile inflammation that either promotes antitumor immunity or supports tumor progression depending on context. Nuclear IL-1α can promote tumor cell proliferation, while extracellular IL-1α activates inflammasome pathways in the tumor microenvironment.

IL1B.description: Interleukin-1 beta is a potent pro-inflammatory cytokine activated by inflammasomes. In cancer, IL-1β promotes tumor growth, angiogenesis, and metastasis. The CANTOS trial showed IL-1β blockade (canakinumab) reduced lung cancer incidence. IL-1β inhibition is being explored in combination with immunotherapy to reduce tumor-promoting inflammation while preserving antitumor immunity.

IL2.description: Interleukin-2 is essential for T cell proliferation and survival. High-dose IL-2 was among the first approved cancer immunotherapies, producing durable responses in metastatic melanoma and renal cell carcinoma. Engineered IL-2 variants (bempegaldesleukin/NKTR-214) preferentially activate effector T cells over regulatory T cells. IL-2 signaling is critical for CAR-T cell persistence and expansion.

IL21.description: Interleukin-21 regulates B cell differentiation and enhances NK and CD8+ T cell cytotoxicity. In immuno-oncology, IL-21 promotes antitumor immunity by enhancing cytotoxic lymphocyte function without expanding regulatory T cells. It is being developed for cancer therapy and is used to improve CAR-T cell manufacturing and persistence through enhanced memory T cell formation.

IL22.description: Interleukin-22 promotes epithelial barrier function and antimicrobial defense. In cancer, IL-22 has dual roles: it promotes tumor cell proliferation and survival through STAT3 activation in colorectal, hepatocellular, and pancreatic cancers, but also supports tissue repair during chemotherapy-induced mucositis. IL-22 signaling in the tumor microenvironment can drive cancer stemness and therapy resistance.

IL27.description: Interleukin-27 has both pro- and anti-inflammatory functions. In cancer immunotherapy, IL-27 has potent antitumor effects: it inhibits tumor angiogenesis, promotes cytotoxic T cell responses, and directly inhibits tumor cell proliferation. IL-27 also induces PD-L1 and IL-10, creating complex immunoregulatory effects. It is being explored as a cancer therapeutic for its unique antitumor mechanisms.

IL3.description: Interleukin-3 (multi-CSF) supports the growth of multiple hematopoietic lineages. In cancer, IL-3 receptor alpha (CD123) is highly expressed on acute myeloid leukemia (AML) blasts and leukemic stem cells, making it an immunotherapy target. CAR-T cells targeting CD123 and antibody-drug conjugates (tagraxofusp) are in development for AML and blastic plasmacytoid dendritic cell neoplasm.

IL36.description: IL-36 cytokines are IL-1 family members that promote inflammation. In cancer, IL-36 family members can enhance antitumor immunity by activating dendritic cells and promoting T cell infiltration into tumors. IL-36γ administration increases tumor immunogenicity and response to checkpoint blockade in preclinical models. IL-36 signaling represents a potential target for cancer immunotherapy.

IL4.description: Interleukin-4 drives Th2 differentiation and M2 macrophage polarization. In cancer, IL-4 generally promotes tumor progression by inducing immunosuppressive M2 macrophages and inhibiting Th1 antitumor responses. However, IL-4 receptor is overexpressed on many tumors, making it a target for immunotoxins and CAR-T therapies. IL-4 fusion toxins are being developed for solid tumors and glioblastoma.

IL6.description: Interleukin-6 is a pleiotropic cytokine elevated in many cancers. IL-6 promotes tumor growth, metastasis, and therapy resistance through STAT3 activation. It contributes to cancer cachexia and immune suppression by expanding MDSCs. IL-6/IL-6R blockade (tocilizumab, siltuximab) is used to manage CAR-T cytokine release syndrome and is being explored to enhance cancer immunotherapy efficacy.

LIF.description: Leukemia inhibitory factor is an IL-6 family cytokine. In cancer, LIF promotes tumor progression by maintaining cancer stem cells, promoting EMT, and supporting immunosuppression through MDSC expansion. LIF is elevated in pancreatic cancer, breast cancer, and glioblastoma. LIF blockade is being explored to enhance chemotherapy and immunotherapy responses in pancreatic cancer.

LTA.description: Lymphotoxin alpha (TNF-beta) is produced by lymphocytes and essential for lymphoid organ development. In cancer, lymphotoxin signaling influences tertiary lymphoid structure formation in tumors, which are associated with improved response to immunotherapy. LTA/LTB signaling shapes the tumor immune microenvironment and affects tumor-draining lymph node function and antitumor immunity.

MCSF.description: Macrophage colony-stimulating factor promotes monocyte and macrophage differentiation. In tumors, CSF1/CSF1R signaling recruits and maintains tumor-associated macrophages (TAMs) that suppress antitumor immunity. CSF1R inhibitors (pexidartinib, PLX3397) are being developed to deplete immunosuppressive TAMs and enhance responses to chemotherapy and checkpoint inhibitors.

NO.description: Nitric oxide (from inducible NOS) is a signaling molecule with antimicrobial effects. In cancer, iNOS has dual roles: low NO levels can promote tumor growth and angiogenesis, while high levels from M1 macrophages are tumoricidal. iNOS expression in the tumor microenvironment correlates with MDSC immunosuppression, and NOS inhibitors are being explored to enhance immunotherapy.

OSM.description: Oncostatin M is an IL-6 family cytokine that regulates cell growth and inflammation. In cancer, OSM promotes tumor progression, metastasis, and EMT through STAT3 activation. It shapes the immunosuppressive tumor microenvironment by recruiting myeloid cells. OSM signaling is associated with poor prognosis in breast cancer and is being targeted in combination with immunotherapy.

TGFB1.description: Transforming growth factor beta 1 regulates cell growth and immune function. TGF-β is a master regulator of tumor immune evasion: it suppresses T cell and NK cell function, induces regulatory T cells, promotes EMT, and excludes T cells from tumors. TGF-β inhibitors (galunisertib, bintrafusp alfa) are being developed to overcome resistance to checkpoint inhibitors in immunologically 'cold' tumors.

TGFB3.description: Transforming growth factor beta 3 is important in wound healing and development. In cancer, TGF-β3 shares immunosuppressive properties with TGF-β1, contributing to tumor immune evasion. It promotes cancer cell invasion and metastasis through EMT induction. TGF-β3 is elevated in certain cancers and contributes to the immunosuppressive tumor microenvironment.

TNFA.description: Tumor necrosis factor alpha is a pro-inflammatory cytokine with complex roles in cancer. While originally named for its ability to cause tumor necrosis, chronic TNF-α often promotes tumor growth, survival, and metastasis. TNF-α contributes to cancer cachexia and can drive resistance to immunotherapy. However, local TNF-α delivery (tasonermin) is used for limb-salvage therapy in sarcoma.

TRAIL.description: TNF-related apoptosis-inducing ligand selectively induces apoptosis in tumor cells while sparing normal cells. TRAIL is expressed by NK cells and cytotoxic T cells and mediates immune surveillance. TRAIL receptor agonists (dulanermin, mapatumumab) have been tested in clinical trials. Combination with chemotherapy or immunotherapy may overcome tumor resistance to TRAIL-induced apoptosis.

TWEAK.description: TNF-like weak inducer of apoptosis regulates cell survival and inflammation. In cancer, TWEAK-Fn14 signaling promotes tumor growth, invasion, and angiogenesis. TWEAK can enhance or suppress antitumor immunity depending on context. Fn14 is highly expressed on many tumor types, making the TWEAK-Fn14 axis a potential target for antibody-drug conjugates and CAR-T therapies.

VEGFA.description: Vascular endothelial growth factor A is the master regulator of tumor angiogenesis. Beyond promoting blood vessel growth, VEGF suppresses antitumor immunity by inhibiting dendritic cell maturation, recruiting MDSCs, and creating an immunosuppressive microenvironment. Anti-VEGF therapy (bevacizumab) combined with checkpoint inhibitors shows synergy by normalizing tumor vasculature and enhancing T cell infiltration.

WNT3A.description: Wnt3a activates canonical Wnt/beta-catenin signaling, regulating proliferation and stem cell maintenance. In cancer, aberrant Wnt signaling drives tumor initiation, cancer stem cell maintenance, and therapy resistance. Wnt pathway activation can exclude T cells from tumors and promote immune evasion. Wnt pathway inhibitors are being developed for combination with immunotherapy in colorectal cancer and other Wnt-driven tumors.

A2M.description: Alpha-2-macroglobulin is a broad-spectrum protease inhibitor. In cancer, A2M can trap and inhibit proteases affecting tumor invasion, and may modulate cytokine activity.

ANGPT1.description: Angiopoietin 1 stabilizes blood vessels through Tie2 receptor. In cancer, Ang1 promotes vascular normalization which can improve drug delivery and T cell infiltration. The balance between Ang1 and Ang2 affects tumor vasculature and immune cell access. Ang1-mediated vessel stabilization may enhance immunotherapy efficacy.

ANGPT2.description: Angiopoietin 2 destabilizes vessels and promotes angiogenesis. In cancer, Ang2 is highly expressed and promotes tumor angiogenesis, immune cell exclusion, and metastasis. Ang2 recruits immunosuppressive Tie2+ macrophages. Anti-Ang2 antibodies combined with anti-VEGF and checkpoint inhibitors show synergistic antitumor effects by normalizing vasculature and enhancing immunity.

CCL11 recruitment of eosinophils may contribute to antitumor immunity through direct cytotoxicity and T cell recruitment, though effects are tumor type-dependent.

CCL17.description: C-C motif chemokine ligand 17 (TARC) attracts Th2 and regulatory T cells via CCR4. In cancer, CCL17 produced by tumor cells and M2 macrophages recruits CCR4+ regulatory T cells to tumors, promoting immune evasion. Anti-CCR4 antibodies (mogamulizumab) deplete regulatory T cells and are approved for adult T-cell leukemia/lymphoma with emerging applications in solid tumors.

CCL18.description: CCL18 (CCL18) is a c-c motif chemokine ligand chemokine that recruits immune cells. In cancer, CC chemokines regulate tumor-associated immune cell infiltration, affecting both antitumor immunity and immunosuppression depending on the specific receptor and cell type recruited.

CCL19.description: C-C motif chemokine ligand 19 guides T cells and dendritic cells to lymph nodes. In cancer, CCL19 is critical for T cell priming and antitumor immunity. CCL19 expression in tumors supports tertiary lymphoid structure formation associated with better prognosis. CAR-T cells armed with CCL19 show enhanced trafficking and antitumor efficacy in preclinical models.

CCL2.description: C-C motif chemokine ligand 2 (MCP-1) recruits monocytes to sites of inflammation. In cancer, CCL2 is a key driver of tumor-associated macrophage (TAM) recruitment, promoting tumor growth, angiogenesis, and metastasis. CCL2/CCR2 inhibitors are being developed to reduce immunosuppressive myeloid infiltration and enhance response to chemotherapy and immunotherapy.

CCL20.description: C-C motif chemokine ligand 20 (MIP-3α) recruits CCR6+ cells including Th17 and dendritic cells. In cancer, CCL20 has dual roles: it can recruit antitumor Th17 cells but also regulatory T cells and immature dendritic cells that promote tolerance. CCL20 is elevated in many cancers and contributes to tumor microenvironment composition.

CCL21.description: C-C motif chemokine ligand 21 guides naive T cells and dendritic cells to lymph nodes via CCR7. In cancer immunotherapy, CCL21-expressing dendritic cell vaccines enhance T cell activation against tumor antigens. CCL21 promotes tertiary lymphoid structure formation in tumors, which correlates with better response to checkpoint inhibitors.

CCL22.description: C-C motif chemokine ligand 22 (MDC) attracts regulatory T cells via CCR4. In cancer, CCL22 is a key mediator of regulatory T cell recruitment to tumors, suppressing antitumor immunity. Tumor cells and M2 macrophages produce CCL22 to create an immunosuppressive microenvironment. Blocking CCL22-CCR4 axis is being explored to enhance immunotherapy.

CCL3.description: C-C motif chemokine ligand 3 (MIP-1α) attracts monocytes and T cells. In immuno-oncology, CCL3 can promote antitumor immunity by recruiting effector T cells and NK cells, but also contributes to chronic inflammation in the tumor microenvironment. CCL3 expression by CAR-T cells enhances tumor trafficking and therapeutic efficacy.

CCL4.description: C-C motif chemokine ligand 4 (MIP-1β) recruits NK cells and immune cells. In cancer, CCL4 is associated with CD8+ T cell infiltration and better prognosis in some tumors. Tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes produce CCL4 to attract additional immune cells. CCL4 expression is part of the inflamed tumor microenvironment signature predictive of immunotherapy response.

CCL4L2.description: CCL4L2 (CCL4L2) is a c-c motif chemokine ligand chemokine that recruits immune cells. In cancer, CC chemokines regulate tumor-associated immune cell infiltration, affecting both antitumor immunity and immunosuppression depending on the specific receptor and cell type recruited.

CCL5.description: C-C motif chemokine ligand 5 (RANTES) attracts T cells and NK cells. In cancer, CCL5 recruits both effector and regulatory T cells to tumors. High CCL5 with CXCL9 expression defines 'hot' tumors with better immunotherapy response. CCL5 produced by cancer cells can also recruit immunosuppressive cells, highlighting its context-dependent role in tumor immunity.

CCL7.description: C-C motif chemokine ligand 7 (MCP-3) recruits monocytes and other immune cells. In cancer, CCL7 contributes to monocyte and macrophage recruitment to tumors. It can promote tumor progression through TAM accumulation but may also enhance antitumor immunity when it recruits inflammatory monocytes. CCL7 is part of the inflammatory chemokine network in the tumor microenvironment.

CCL8.description: C-C motif chemokine ligand 8 (MCP-2) attracts monocytes and lymphocytes. In the tumor microenvironment, CCL8 is produced by cancer-associated fibroblasts and macrophages, contributing to myeloid cell recruitment. CCL8 expression correlates with immune infiltration patterns and may influence response to immunotherapy in various solid tumors.

CXCL1.description: C-X-C motif chemokine ligand 1 (GROα) is a potent neutrophil chemoattractant. In cancer, CXCL1 promotes tumor angiogenesis, metastasis, and recruits immunosuppressive neutrophils (PMN-MDSCs). CXCL1 signaling through CXCR2 supports tumor progression in pancreatic, colorectal, and breast cancers. CXCR2 inhibitors are being developed to block this pro-tumorigenic axis.

CXCL10.description: C-X-C motif chemokine ligand 10 (IP-10) attracts activated T cells and NK cells. CXCL10 is a critical mediator of antitumor immunity, recruiting CXCR3+ effector T cells to tumors. It is induced by IFN-γ and is a biomarker for checkpoint inhibitor response. CXCL10 expression is being used to identify immunotherapy-responsive patients and 'hot' tumor phenotypes.

CXCL11.description: C-X-C motif chemokine ligand 11 (I-TAC) attracts activated T cells via CXCR3. In cancer, CXCL11 works with CXCL9/10 to recruit effector T cells to tumors. It is part of the IFN-γ-induced antitumor immune response. High CXCL11 correlates with better prognosis and immunotherapy response in multiple cancer types.

CXCL12.description: CXCL12 (CXCL12) is a c-x-c motif chemokine ligand chemokine involved in immune cell trafficking. In cancer, CXC chemokines regulate tumor angiogenesis, immune cell recruitment, and metastasis. CXCR3 ligands (CXCL9/10/11) attract effector T cells, while CXCR2 ligands recruit immunosuppressive neutrophils.

CXCL13.description: C-X-C motif chemokine ligand 13 (BCA-1) attracts B cells to lymphoid follicles. In cancer, CXCL13 expression indicates tertiary lymphoid structure formation in tumors, which is associated with favorable prognosis and response to immunotherapy. CXCL13+ CD4 T cells represent a tumor-reactive population predictive of checkpoint inhibitor response.

CXCL14.description: C-X-C motif chemokine ligand 14 (BRAK) has antimicrobial activity. In cancer, CXCL14 shows tumor-suppressive properties: it recruits NK cells and dendritic cells, inhibits tumor angiogenesis, and suppresses tumor growth. CXCL14 expression is often silenced in tumors through promoter methylation, and its restoration may enhance antitumor immunity.

CXCL17.description: CXCL17 (CXCL17) is a c-x-c motif chemokine ligand chemokine involved in immune cell trafficking. In cancer, CXC chemokines regulate tumor angiogenesis, immune cell recruitment, and metastasis. CXCR3 ligands (CXCL9/10/11) attract effector T cells, while CXCR2 ligands recruit immunosuppressive neutrophils.

CXCL2.description: C-X-C motif chemokine ligand 2 (GROβ) recruits neutrophils and MDSCs. In the tumor microenvironment, CXCL2 promotes neutrophil recruitment that can suppress antitumor T cell responses. CXCL2 contributes to pre-metastatic niche formation and supports cancer cell survival. Targeting CXCL2-CXCR2 signaling may enhance immunotherapy efficacy.

CXCL3.description: C-X-C motif chemokine ligand 3 (GROγ) attracts neutrophils and promotes angiogenesis. In cancer, CXCL3 shares functions with CXCL1/2 in recruiting pro-tumorigenic myeloid cells. CXCL3 expression by cancer cells promotes tumor growth and metastasis through CXCR2 signaling. It contributes to the immunosuppressive tumor microenvironment.

CXCL5.description: C-X-C motif chemokine ligand 5 (ENA-78) recruits neutrophils and promotes angiogenesis. In cancer, CXCL5 drives tumor progression through MDSC recruitment and angiogenesis promotion. It is elevated in colorectal, pancreatic, and hepatocellular carcinoma. CXCL5 promotes EMT and metastasis, and targeting the CXCL5-CXCR2 axis may enhance antitumor immunity.

CXCL6.description: C-X-C motif chemokine ligand 6 (GCP-2) attracts neutrophils with antimicrobial activity. In cancer, CXCL6 can have both pro- and anti-tumorigenic effects depending on context. It recruits neutrophils that may be immunosuppressive (N2) or tumoricidal (N1). CXCL6 expression in the tumor microenvironment affects treatment response.

CXCL8.description: Interleukin-8 (CXCL8) is a major neutrophil chemoattractant. In cancer, IL-8 is one of the most important pro-tumorigenic chemokines: it promotes angiogenesis, recruits immunosuppressive MDSCs, enhances EMT, and maintains cancer stem cells. High IL-8 predicts poor response to immunotherapy. Anti-IL-8 antibodies are being developed to enhance checkpoint inhibitor efficacy.

CXCL9.description: C-X-C motif chemokine ligand 9 (MIG) attracts activated T cells via CXCR3. CXCL9 is a key marker of inflamed 'hot' tumors: it is induced by IFN-γ and recruits effector CD8+ T cells. High CXCL9 expression predicts response to checkpoint inhibitors. CXCL9 is part of the T cell-inflamed gene expression signature used to stratify patients for immunotherapy.

GRP.description: Gastrin-releasing peptide (GRP) is a bombesin-like neuropeptide that stimulates gastrin release and cell proliferation. In cancer, GRP promotes tumor growth through autocrine signaling in small cell lung cancer, prostate cancer, and other tumors. GRP receptor (GRPR) is overexpressed in many cancers and is a target for imaging and radionuclide therapy.
